<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-03-24T23:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-03-24T23:30:00-05:00" n="22" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">845C.00/3–2547: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Rangoon</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Packer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Rangoon</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-03-25T11:00:00+06:30">March 25,
                                    1947—11 a.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>234. Supreme Council United Hill Peoples now in session at Tounggyi has
                            just decided Hill Peoples will participate in work of Constituent
                            Assembly. Manner of participation still to be worked out.<note n="50" xml:id="d22fn50">Telegram 335, April 28, from Rangoon, reported the
                                signing on April 24 at Maymyo of the “unanimous report Frontier
                                Areas Inquiry Committee on best method associating frontier areas
                                peoples with framing Burma’s new constitution”. (845C.9111
                                RR/4–2847) This Committee was headed by Lt. Col. D. R.
                                Rees-Williams, member of the British House of Commons; for text of
                                report, see British Cmd. 7138.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Repeated London as 51.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Packer</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>